# Episode 0001 – What is Articulate?

## Introduction

If someone asked me what Articulate is, my answer has changed many times over the years.

It started as a small side project to solve problems I experienced as a software architect. Over time those ideas evolved, converged and occasionally failed. Each experiment taught me something new until eventually they formed a vision that I genuinely wanted to build.

Like many of my personal projects, Articulate exists primarily as a learning exercise. It allows me to explore new ideas, experiment with AI-native architecture and improve my own skills. If the result becomes useful to other architects, then even better.

Most of my projects exist to scratch my own itch. Articulate is no different.

This journal documents that journey.

---

# The Problems I Wanted to Solve

Over the years I have worked with many organisations, projects and architects. Although every company is different, I kept encountering the same problems over and over again.

None of them were caused by a lack of intelligent people. They were caused by the nature of architecture itself. Architecture is constantly evolving, spread across many sources of information, and rarely understood completely by any one person.

Articulate isn't attempting to solve a single problem. It is an attempt to improve many small frustrations that, together, make architecture far more difficult than it needs to be.

---

## Understanding the Current State ("As-Is")

I have yet to work in an organisation that has a complete understanding of its current architecture.

Architecture knowledge lives everywhere.

* Wiki pages
* Confluence
* Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)
* Git repositories
* Diagrams
* Slide decks
* Cloud configurations
* Source code
* Meeting notes
* Production telemetry
* People's memories

Some of this information is accurate.

Some is incomplete.

Some directly contradicts other information.

Even organisations that invest heavily in Enterprise Architecture Management (EAM) platforms often struggle to keep them accurate. The quality of the model is only as good as the information people manage to keep up to date.

Whenever I interview for a new role I often ask a simple question:

> "How well do you understand your current architecture?"

Nobody has ever answered "perfectly", and I wouldn't expect them to.

Starting a new architecture role usually involves watching old recordings, reading outdated documentation, interviewing subject matter experts and slowly piecing together fragments until a picture begins to emerge.

The reality is that architects spend a surprising amount of time simply trying to understand what already exists.

---

## Keeping Documentation Relevant

Architecture documentation begins to lose value the moment it is written.

That doesn't mean it becomes wrong. It simply becomes less trustworthy over time.

Some documents describe systems that no longer exist.

Others remain perfectly valid because those parts of the architecture have barely changed.

The problem is knowing which is which.

Rather than simply asking "When was this document written?", I want to answer questions such as:

* Is this still relevant?
* Which architecture baseline does it describe?
* Has anything changed since it was created?
* Should it be reviewed?

Documentation shouldn't just exist.

It should have context.

---

## Creating New Solution Designs

Every problem is different.

Some solution designs require deep technical analysis while others are primarily concerned with business change.

Over the years I have developed mental checklists that help me discover missing requirements, identify assumptions and explore architectural trade-offs.

I would like those checklists to become part of the tooling itself—not to replace architectural thinking, but to help ensure important considerations are not overlooked.

---

## Recording Architectural Decisions

Architecture Decision Records have become increasingly popular, and rightly so.

The problem is rarely writing ADRs.

The problem is managing them.

Questions such as these are surprisingly difficult to answer:

* Which ADRs applied to Architecture Version 3?
* Which decisions were later reversed?
* Were those decisions ever implemented?
* Why did we change our minds?

Architectural decisions should form part of the historical record of the architecture rather than existing as isolated markdown files.

---

## Understanding the Impact of Change

Architecture is fundamentally about enabling change.

Every change introduces risk.

If we don't fully understand the current architecture, we cannot accurately predict the consequences of changing it.

Questions I regularly ask include:

* What systems depend on this service?
* What capabilities will be affected?
* What qualities become weaker if we remove this component?
* What is the blast radius of this change?

These questions are often answerable—but only after significant investigation.

I'd like them to become routine.

---

## Understanding Feasibility

One of the most valuable contributions an architect can make is determining whether something is actually feasible.

Not whether it is technically possible—that is usually the easy part—but whether it is realistic within the constraints of the organisation.

Questions such as:

* Have we solved something similar before?
* Do we already have the capability?
* Are we introducing unnecessary complexity?
* What assumptions are we making?
* What risks have we overlooked?

Feasibility is often determined through experience and investigation. I believe AI can become a valuable collaborator in that process by surfacing evidence, identifying assumptions and challenging architectural thinking.

---

## Understanding Architectural Maturity

Most organisations know they could improve.

Few know where they should improve first.

Architecture maturity models already exist, but they are often treated as one-off assessments rather than something that evolves continuously.

I would like architectural maturity to become another lens through which the architecture can be viewed, helping identify opportunities where relatively small improvements could significantly increase resilience, maintainability or operational excellence.

---

## Finding Architectural Information

Modern systems are becoming increasingly distributed.

More services.

More integrations.

More cloud platforms.

More moving parts.

Finding information often becomes a manual exercise involving multiple tools and conversations.

Sometimes I simply want to ask questions such as:

* What connects to this service?
* Which systems consume this event?
* Where is this capability implemented?
* Which applications use this cloud resource?

Architects shouldn't need to remember where information lives.

They should be able to ask questions.

---

## Stop Drawing Diagrams Manually

This one is entirely personal.

I don't particularly enjoy drawing architecture diagrams.

I much prefer Diagrams as Code using tools such as C4, Mermaid and PlantUML.

Even then, I don't believe diagrams should be manually maintained.

They should be generated from the architecture model itself.

A diagram should be a view of the architecture—not the architecture.

---

# Why Build This Now?

Many of these ideas have been possible in theory for years.

In practice, they weren't feasible.

Architecture information is messy.

It is incomplete.

It contains uncertainty, contradictions and gaps.

Traditional software generally expects structured information with definitive answers.

Architectural knowledge rarely looks like that.

Recent advances in AI have changed the equation.

Large language models are remarkably good at working with incomplete information, synthesising multiple sources, identifying contradictions and asking follow-up questions when confidence is low.

They don't replace architects.

They augment architectural thinking.

That makes many of the ideas behind Articulate practical for the first time.

---

# How Articulate Responds

Rather than being another documentation repository, Articulate attempts to become an architectural companion.

Its purpose is not to replace architects or generate documents.

Its purpose is to help architects understand, reason about and evolve architecture over time.

Several core capabilities support that vision.

## Discovery

Discovery operates through three complementary lenses.

* **Landscape** – understanding the organisation, business capabilities and relationships across the enterprise.
* **Systems** – discovering the technical structure, technologies, integrations and deployment landscape.
* **Domain** – understanding behaviour, capabilities, outcomes and business intent.

Rather than assuming perfect information, discovery captures claims, evidence and confidence.

The model accepts uncertainty because uncertainty is a natural part of architecture.

---

## Architecture Baselines

Source code has versions.

Infrastructure has versions.

Architecture should have versions too.

Articulate introduces the concept of architecture baselines.

Every design, document and architectural decision belongs to a particular architectural state.

As architecture evolves, new baselines are created, allowing architects to understand not only the current architecture but also how it evolved over time.

This becomes particularly valuable during long-running transformation programmes where multiple transitional states may exist simultaneously.

---

## The Architecture Knowledge Model

At the heart of Articulate is a continuously evolving architectural model.

Discovery enriches it.

Architectural decisions refine it.

Solution designs extend it.

Evidence increases confidence.

Rather than storing isolated documents, Articulate attempts to model the architecture itself.

Knowledge graphs may ultimately become one implementation of this model, but the architectural model is the important concept.

---

## Explore

Once the model exists, architects should be able to explore it naturally.

Instead of searching through folders or documentation, they can ask questions, navigate relationships and generate views that help explain the architecture.

Information should become conversational.

---

## Impact Analysis

Understanding the consequences of change becomes significantly easier when the relationships between systems, capabilities and decisions are understood.

Rather than manually tracing dependencies, Articulate aims to help identify potential risks, affected capabilities and areas requiring further investigation before change begins.

---

## Solution Design

Articulate is not intended to design systems for architects.

Instead, it aims to become a collaborative design partner.

Helping discover requirements.

Highlighting constraints.

Questioning assumptions.

Presenting trade-offs.

Recording the reasoning behind architectural decisions.

---

## Gap Analysis

Every new solution should begin by understanding what already exists.

Can an existing capability be reused?

Does another team already provide the required functionality?

What genuinely needs building?

Gap analysis should reduce duplication and encourage better architectural reuse across an organisation.

---

# Looking Ahead

Articulate is an experiment.

Some ideas will succeed.

Some will fail.

Many will evolve into something completely different.

That is exactly why this journal exists.

Rather than documenting only the finished software, I want to document the architectural thinking behind it.

The software is evidence of that thinking—not the end goal itself.

Ultimately, Articulate is an exploration of architectural intelligence.

A long-term experiment into how AI can help architects understand complex systems, reason about change, preserve knowledge and make better decisions.

Whether it succeeds or not, I hope the journey itself proves valuable.
